  "content": "\u003cp\u003e\u003cspan class=\"h-card\" translate=\"no\"\u003e\u003ca href=\"https://hachyderm.io/@markd\" class=\"u-url mention\"\u003e@\u003cspan\u003emarkd\u003c/span\u003e\u003c/a\u003e\u003c/span\u003e Errgroup allows you to constrain how many concurrent goroutines are running in the group. This is annoyingly complex logic to do manually and is easy to get wrong.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003eFor the primary use-case of errgroup (many goroutines, return the first error), it works amazingly. I know I\u0026#39;m asking to expand it to behave differently, but it\u0026#39;s really good at what it is designed to do.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003eThe context cancelling logic: Creating a new errgroup returns a new context that will automatically be cancelled when an error is returned from any of the goroutine functions.\u003c/p\u003e\u003cp\u003eAll of this adds up to an incredibly useful abstraction that doesn\u0026#39;t require you to manage a mutex, manage cancelling a context, manage limiting parallelism of workers in the pool. If you want all of those features, it can get extremely complex. Even in your example, I\u0026#39;ve seen so many subtle bugs from some conditions not calling wg.Done() in all flows. Errgroup simply removes that class of error.\u003c/p\u003e",
